Fragility of the Flat World
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman said this. Friedman chose this provocative title for his best-selling book to draw attention to the remarkable impact of technology on the global economy.
Distances are shrinking.
Geographic barriers can no longer provide protection easily.
European and American manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals all have to face the challenge of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they talk to may well be in India.
Skeptics point out the limitations of Friedman's metaphor.
As one person put it, the world is not flat but "hilly."
The contour lines of economic activity around the world show peaks of prosperity and valleys of scarcity.
Moreover, distance still matters.
Even neighboring countries with low tariff barriers, like Canada and the United States, engage in much more domestic trade than cross-border trade.
Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, but Vancouver trades far more with Toronto, which is farther away, than with nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman makes an important point.
Globalization can be defined as interdependence among different continents, a history as long as that of humanity, witnessing migrations of race and religion, and ancient trade along the Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different; it is developing faster and deeper.
In 1868, with the first transatlantic telegraph cable laid, Europe and America could communicate within just one minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes described how a wealthy Briton living in London could place orders for goods from all over the world via telephone and wait at home for delivery in the afternoon.
But Keynes's British man was an exception.
Today, millions upon millions of people around the globe can buy goods from all over the world at their local supermarkets.
Similarly, there was instantaneous global communication 20 years ago, but it was beyond the economic means of most people.
Now, almost anyone can walk into a internet cafe and gain capabilities that were previously available only to governments, multinational corporations, and a few wealthy individuals or institutions with large budgets.
The significant declines in computing, communication, and transportation costs have made technology more accessible.
Just ten years ago, two-thirds of internet users were concentrated in the United States.
Today, US internet users make up less than a quarter of the global user base.
Knowledge is power, and today, the number of people who possess it has reached the highest level in human history.
Non-state institutions now possess capabilities that were previously held only by governments.
National states, as subjects of world politics, will not change their status temporarily, but they must learn to share this vast stage with more participants, including institutions like Oxfam, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like al-Qaeda.
But this flattening process can be reversed.
Similar situations have occurred before.
In 1914, the world economy was highly integrated, but over the next thirty years, economic interdependence among countries continually declined.
It was not until 1970 that the global economy restored the level of integration it had once achieved, though it was still hampered by the Iron Curtain.
World War I was the catalyst for this reversal, and during the two World Wars and one global Cold War, we witnessed a decrease in economic globalization alongside an increase in military globalization.
This reflected deeper issues of domestic inequality caused by economic development in the 19th century.
Politics failed to adapt to economic developments, leading to abnormal ideologies—fascism and communism—which contributed to the fragmentation of both nations and the world.
After World War II, Western welfare state systems wove a safety net for people harmed by economic changes, encouraging them to accept the benefits brought by international economic interdependence.
Some analysts see China's role today as very similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising powers troubled by domestic inequality, constantly moving towards nationalist sentiments, challenging dominant forces, and ultimately leading to a reversal of economic globalization progress through world wars.
While the U.S. and China’s economies are highly interdependent today, was not the case for Britain and Germany before 1914 either.
But such reasoning is flawed.
After 1900, German industrial production had already surpassed that of Britain.
But even maintaining its current high growth rate, China’s economy is unlikely to catch up with the United States for at least two decades.
A greater threat to the flat world may be the non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology.
On September 11, 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in a surprise attack than the Japanese government did in Pearl Harbor in 1941.
I call this phenomenon privatization of war.
If such powers acquired nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would be turned upside down.
Then, movement of people and goods across borders would become much more difficult.
If these powers disrupted oil exports from the Persian Gulf, which holds two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic recession like that of the 1930s could further strengthen protectionist forces.
Technology and policy are the two major drivers of globalization.
To date, policies have further reinforced the flattening effects of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken the lead in promoting policies to remove barriers.
But the events described above could reverse such policies.
Certain critics of globalization might be willing to see such a outcome.
But such an outcome, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst conditions in two areas—that is, a reversal of the trend toward economic globalization of communication and power, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization become more entrenched, such as wars, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of diseases.
If that were to happen, the Flat World would turn into a desert.
